pkg_lib v1.0.10 | Apr 24 2026:

  [Fix] pkg_fhs_verify_farm: add `[[ -O "$manifest_path" ]]` ownership
      check mirroring pkg_manifest_load. An attacker-writable manifest
      could otherwise cause pkg_fhs_verify_farm (run as root) to destroy
      a legitimate regular file and replace it with a symlink to an
      arbitrary target. Manifest absence still returns 0 silently; a
      present-but-foreign-owned manifest now errors and returns 1.
      Surfaced by /r-audit security pass (post-v1.0.7 remediation
      audit).

  [Change] pkg/pkg_gen.sh: removed 14 unicode banner separators across
      7 section blocks — extends v1.0.10's comment-discipline cleanup to
      the build-time generator that was missed by the first pass. Section
      boundaries now use blank lines per Code Comments rule. Zero
      functional change; shellcheck count unchanged (0).

  [Change] files/pkg_lib.sh: removed 206 signature-restatement lines from
      42 multi-line function-header blocks — deleted `# Arguments:` /
      `#   $N — name` / default `# Returns 0/1` lines that restated what
      the code declared on the next line. Load-bearing prose preserved
      intact: non-obvious return semantics, side-effect documentation,
      security rationale (AWK/shell injection vectors, symlink-directory
      gotchas, eval-guard validation), platform quirks (GNU vs BSD stat,
      FreeBSD guards, CentOS 6 usr-merge), bash 4.1 compat notes
      (indirect expansion, no declare -n), detection-chain documentation,
      and the full pkg_config_merge conditional-expression safety header.
      One-line-header style per rdf core profile comment-discipline rule.
      Zero functional change; shellcheck count unchanged (0); load-bearing
      whitelist diff content-identical.

  [Change] PKG_LIB_VERSION: 1.0.9 → 1.0.10

pkg_lib v1.0.9 | Apr 07 2026:

  [Fix] pkg_config_merge: anchor variable detection to a real shell
      assignment regex (^[[:space:]]*[A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_]*=). Pre-1.0.9
      treated any line containing `=` as VAR=value, corrupting
      conditional expressions like `[ "$X" = "1" ]` and
      `[[ "$Y" == "auto" ]]` into `[ "$X"= "1" ]` / `[[ "$Y"== "auto" ]]`
      by stripping the space before the operator. The merge function
      remains semantically unsafe for files with conditional assignments
      (branches collapse) — documented in the function header. Regression
      test added in tests/09-config.bats covering bash conditional
      passthrough plus a `bash -n` parse check on the merged output.
      Surfaced as a class of CI failures in APF where importconf merged
      internals.conf on every reinstall
